  "prompt": "What is the difference between orthographic projection and isometric projection?",
  "response": "Here are the key differences between orthographic projection and isometric projection:\n\nOrthographic Projection:\n1. Shows object from multiple fixed views (front, top, side)\n2. Represents true dimensions and shapes\n3. Two-dimensional representation\n4. Uses 90-degree angles between projection planes\n5. Provides precise measurements\n6. Used in technical and engineering drawings\n7. No perspective or foreshortening\n8. Each view shows object exactly as it appears from that angle\n\nIsometric Projection:\n1. Shows object in single three-dimensional view\n2. Uses 30-degree angles between axes\n3. Creates illusion of depth and perspective\n4. Provides simplified 3D representation\n5. Allows viewer to see multiple sides simultaneously\n6. Used in architectural and design visualization\n7. Slightly distorts actual object dimensions\n8. Maintains equal scale along all three axes\n9. More visually engaging and intuitive representation\n\nPrimary difference is that orthographic projection provides precise technical views, while isometric projection offers a more comprehensive 3D visual representation of an object.",
